#### **Performance Testing (Conceptual)**

For performance testing, tools like **Artillery** (for API load testing) or **Lighthouse/WebPageTest** (for frontend performance) would be integrated.

**Example `artillery.yml` for backend API load testing:**
```yaml
config:
  target: "http://localhost:5000/api/v1" # Or your deployed backend URL
  phases:
    - duration: 60 # seconds
      arrivalRate: 20 # new users per second
      name: "Warm up"
    - duration: 120
      arrivalRate: 50
      rampTo: 100
      name: "Ramp up load"
    - duration: 60
      arrivalRate: 100
      name: "Sustained load"
  payload:
    # Path to CSV containing user credentials for login
    path: "users.csv"
    fields:
      - "email"
      - "password"
  defaults:
    headers:
      Content-Type: "application/json"
scenarios:
  - name: "User Login & Fetch Data"
    flow:
      - post:
          url: "/auth/login"
          json:
            email: "{{ email }}"
            password: "{{ password }}"
          capture:
            json: "$.token"
            as: "authToken"
      - get:
          url: "/target-databases"
          headers:
            Authorization: "Bearer {{ authToken }}"
          match:
            status: 200
      - get:
          url: "/recommendations"
          headers:
            Authorization: "Bearer {{ authToken }}"
          match:
            status: 200
      # Simulate creation of a report (less frequent, admin role)
      - post:
          url: "/analysis-reports"
          headers:
            Authorization: "Bearer {{ authToken }}"
          json:
            title: "Load Test Report - {{ $randomNumber(1000, 9999) }}"
            description: "Generated by load test"
            targetDatabaseId: "existing_db_id" # You'd need an ID from seed or pre-create
            analystId: "{{ $uuid }}" # Should use a valid analyst ID, or if admin, use {{ $user.id }}
          match:
            status: 201
```

To run Artillery: `artillery run artillery.yml`

This would require generating a `users.csv` with a large number of test users, and possibly pre-seeding an `existing_db_id` and an admin `analystId` into the database for tests.

